title: Louisa Van Velsor Whitman to Walt Whitman, 7 December [1869]
text: '69 ?December 7 My dear Walti got your letter yesterday morning it come real quick i was quite astonished to see it was wrote sundaySunday afternoon George has been home and left yesterday in a tremendous snow storm he went to new yorkNew York to send you 200 dollrsdollars by express i suppossuppose walterWalter you have got it all right he sent some to Jeff also) well waltWalt we have stood it through the storm it was a very bad storm indeedi am about the same as usual feel pretty well your aunt beccaBecca is better old mrsMrs. man is back from mobealMobile waltWalt the clapp i wrote about is the one hellen priceHelen Price spoke to you about being to the falanks Jersey) poor mrMr. Beecher gets it right and leftwalt when you write again tell all you gain about the new attorney Ge George dontdon't think he will be to camdenCamden all winter as he thinks the brooklynBrooklyn board will stop having pipe made if he staidstayed for the new yorkNew York board he would lose his place on the brooklynBrooklyn)good bie walterWalter dear i looked for mrMr. OconorO'Connor mondayMonday and tuesdayTuesdayfrom dear mother Louisa Van Velsor Whitman to Walt Whitman, 7 December [1869]
